        "id": 2070378,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2016-12-04T01:46:03.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Karl K\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n Karl K:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Good fill into base neck.</p>\n<p>Quite a bit of color variation, from watery rim to orange to garnet to medium red.</p>\n<p>A nicely aromatic nose of cigar ash, cocoa, smoke, nuts, wet forest floor, and faint amounts of blood orange and red currants. Also a slight metallic note.</p>\n<p>One of the first impressions on the palate is a nice honeyed sweetness, with further impressions of a silky palate - nicely resolved tannins - a red earth quality and mild flavors of red fruits: currants again and cherry and strawberry.</p>\n<p>Quite fine. (Doggone good.)</p>\n<p>Anyone know why the metallic aroma would be there? I have noticed it before in other older Bordeauxes.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>The metallic aroma (and flavor, no?) is likely reduction. This wine really blossoms with a few hours\u2019 decant in fact. I worked through a case of magnums over the last two years, starting with pop and pour and ending up with three hours\u2019 double decant. The last bottle showed the best!</p>\n<p>Pape Clement made some seriously good wines back in the day, in both strong (e.g. '61, '64) and weaker vintages (e.g. '52, '81). The 1970 is one of the most red-fruited vintages I have encountered. Typically the fruit tones are quite dark and degraded.</p>",
