      {
        "id": 2070399,
        "name": "Karl K@zaks",
        "username": "Karl_K",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/k/df705f/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2016-12-04T02:37:26.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"William Kelley\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n William Kelley:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Karl K\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n Karl K:</div>\n<blockquote></blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>The metallic aroma (and flavor, no?) is likely reduction. This wine really blossoms with a few hours\u2019 decant in fact. I worked through a case of magnums over the last two years, starting with pop and pour and ending up with three hours\u2019 double decant. The last bottle showed the best!</p>\n<p>Pape Clement made some seriously good wines back in the day, in both strong (e.g. '61, '64) and weaker vintages (e.g. '52, '81). The 1970 is one of the most red-fruited vintages I have encountered. Typically the fruit tones are quite dark and degraded.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Thanks for the feedback, I appreciate it!</p>\n<p>Revisiting the wine now I do see the metallic bit has left, and reduction  makes sense b/c initial note was after pop n pour. More cedar notes now.</p>\n<p>When you say 1970 a red fruited vintage, and other vintages darker fruited, are you referring specifically to Pape Clement or the vintage overall, across chateaux?</p>\n<p>FWIW 1969 Beychevelle I tasted in April was more red-fruited than this, but also less concentrated, less complex.</p>",
